    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for explaining. so basically it's just a way to make sure the money doesn't go to the wrong person before the house is actually mine? also who exactly is the person or company that actually holds the money? is it just a bank or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you're absolutely right; it acts as a safety net to ensure the funds don't leave your control until the legal transfer of ownership is complete. In Toronto, this is typically held by a title company, a lawyer, or sometimes a specialized bank, not just a generic bank account. They act as the neutral intermediary that verifies all closing documents before releasing the money to the seller's lawyer or account.\n\nTo be perfectly clear, you generally don't \"own\" the escrow account itself, but rather you have a contractual obligation to fund it. Your realtor or closing agent will handle the paperwork to set this up, and you'll likely see a specific line item for these \"escrow fees\" in your final closing statement. As long as you pay the required deposit upfront, the process is straightforward and designed to protect your investment.",
