    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i guess i'm just a bit nervous about the \"holding\" part of it. it feels weird having this big chunk of money just sitting there with a third party. is there any risk of them just... losing it or mishandling it? like how do we know they're actually guarding it properly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That feeling of unease is completely normal, but rest assured that the financial institutions holding the money in Toronto are heavily regulated and insured against exactly these kinds of risks. If a title company or lawyer were to mishandle funds, they are personally liable, and the funds are often protected under specific provincial laws designed to prevent theft or loss. The system isn't just a passive \"holding\" of cash; it involves strict audits, daily reconciliations, and multiple layers of oversight to ensure the money stays safe until the very second it's legally required to move.\n\nIn the worst-case scenario, where a custodian fails, you would be covered by insurance or restitution plans, so your money is never truly left in the air. It's designed to be a fortress of security, ensuring that the transaction only completes when both parties are legally bound to their new status. Once everything is signed and verified, the funds are released immediately and directly to the appropriate parties.\n\nThink of it as the ultimate safety net required by law, where any single point of failure is mitigated by strict regulations and professional accountability. Your realtor and closing agent will be able to point you to the specific escrow account number and confirm the institution's credentials, giving you peace",
      "source": "target",
